  "chunk_index": 34,
  "summary": "Hercule Poirot confronts Eve Carpenter regarding her attempt to bribe a man to withhold a message and provide her with a false alibi. Poirot warns her that a jury will likely favor the testimony of a servant over hers and observes that she attempts to resolve all problems with money. During the exchange, Poirot makes a cryptic remark about her past, noting her resemblance to an \"ugly duckling\" and mentioning her former use of braces. Eve refuses to hire Poirot, stating that he is already working for James Bentley, the man accused of killing a janitor. Following her departure, Poirot reflects on the possibility that Mrs. Upward telephoned several women, including Dierdre Henderson and Evelyn Carrington.\n\nWhile at a residence, Poirot discovers a photograph in a desk drawer but hides it under a cushion when Moll enters the room. Moll mentions that her husband, Johnny, refuses to sell an oil painting of an ancestor who may have met a terrible end at sea.\n\nLater, Poirot visits Dr. Darnell's house and speaks with Mrs. Darrendell. She admits that Mrs. Upward called her around six o'clock on the night of her death, requesting a visit after nine o'clock because the house would be empty. Mrs. Darrendell explains she failed to go because she fell asleep, and she expresses both guilt and fear regarding the situation.\n\nFinally, Poirot discusses the investigation with Inspector Spence. They consider the theory that Mrs. Upward might be Eva Kahn, also known as Evelyn Hope, who may have faked her death in Australia twenty years prior to marry a wealthy industrialist. They note that Mrs. Upward's maiden name may have been Hargreaves and discuss whether Mrs. Upward killed Mrs. McIntyre to protect her secret.",
